            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this ASCE 7-22 snow load calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool implements the core ASCE 7-22 roof snow load equations
                for flat and sloped roofs and adds a transparent breakdown of
                all intermediate factors. It is designed for quick checks,
                comparisons between roof configurations, and teaching younger
                engineers how the provisions work.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Ground snow load pg</h3>
              <p>
                The starting point is the
                <strong>ground snow load</strong> \(p_g\) in psf. For ASCE 7-22
                you typically obtain pg from:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The official ASCE 7 Hazard Tool (select ASCE 7-22 and enter
                  your site location), or
                </li>
                <li>
                  State or local amendments that override the national maps.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Enter this value directly in the calculator. The tool does not
                fetch pg automatically; it assumes you have already determined
                the correct mapped value.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Exposure factor Ce</h3>
              <p>
                ASCE 7-22 defines an <strong>exposure factor</strong> \(C_e\) to
                account for wind exposure and snow scouring. This calculator
                approximates Ce based on the selected exposure category:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Exposure B</strong> (urban/suburban, wooded): Ce ≈ 1.0
                </li>
                <li><strong>Exposure C</strong> (open terrain): Ce ≈ 0.9</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Exposure D</strong> (near large bodies of water): Ce ≈
                  0.8
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                These are typical values for illustration. For final design, use
                the exact Ce values and tables in ASCE 7-22.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Thermal factor Ct</h3>
              <p>
                The <strong>thermal factor</strong> \(C_t\) adjusts for heat
                loss through the roof:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Unheated / cold roof</strong>: Ct ≈ 1.2</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Ventilated, standard insulation</strong>: Ct ≈ 1.0
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Warm roof (significant heat loss)</strong>: Ct ≈ 0.85
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Warm roofs shed more snow, so Ct is lower. Again, confirm exact
                values in the standard.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Importance factor Is</h3>
              <p>
                The <strong>importance factor</strong> \(I_s\) depends on the
                Risk Category of the building:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Risk Category I: Is ≈ 0.8</li>
                <li>Risk Category II: Is ≈ 1.0</li>
                <li>Risk Category III: Is ≈ 1.1</li>
                <li>Risk Category IV: Is ≈ 1.2</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Higher-risk facilities (hospitals, emergency centers) use larger
                Is to reduce the probability of failure.
              </p>

              <h3>5. Flat roof snow load pf</h3>
              <p>
                For flat roofs (or sloped roofs treated as flat), the calculator
                uses the familiar relationship:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( p_f = 0.7 \, C_e \, C_t \, I_s \, p_g \)
              </div>
              <p>
                The tool also enforces a
                <strong>minimum flat roof snow load</strong>. If you leave the
                “minimum pf” field blank, it applies a typical minimum of 20 psf
                where applicable. You can override this with your own minimum to
                match local code requirements.
              </p>

              <h3>6. Sloped roof snow load ps</h3>
              <p>
                For sloped roofs, ASCE 7-22 applies a
                <strong>slope factor</strong> \(C_s\) to reduce snow load as the
                roof gets steeper. This calculator approximates Cs based on the
                roof angle:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>0–15°: Cs ≈ 1.0 (no reduction)</li>
                <li>15–30°: linear reduction from 1.0 down to ≈ 0.7</li>
                <li>30–60°: linear reduction from ≈ 0.7 down to ≈ 0.2</li>
                <li>&gt; 60°: Cs ≈ 0 (snow generally does not accumulate)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>The sloped roof snow load is then:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">\( p_s = C_s \, p_f \)</div>

              <h3>7. Snow drift surcharge pd</h3>
              <p>
                Roofs adjacent to higher roofs or with parapets can accumulate
                <strong>drifted snow</strong>. ASCE 7-22 provides detailed
                procedures for computing drift height and surcharge. This
                calculator uses a simplified relationship to estimate a drift
                surcharge:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( p_d \approx 0.43 \, \sqrt{p_g} \, h_d \)
              </div>
              <p>
                where \(h_d\) is the height difference or parapet height in
                feet. The result is capped to avoid unrealistically large
                drifts. The tool reports:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Estimated drift height hd (ft)</li>
                <li>Drift surcharge pd (psf)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For critical structures or unusual geometries, always follow the
                full ASCE 7-22 drift procedure.
              </p>

              <h3>8. Rain-on-snow surcharge</h3>
              <p>
                In some climates, ASCE 7-22 requires a
                <strong>rain-on-snow surcharge</strong> (commonly taken as 5
                psf) to account for rain falling on an existing snowpack. If you
                enable this option, the calculator adds:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">\( p_r \approx 5 \, \text{psf} \)</div>
              <p>to the balanced and drifted roof snow loads.</p>

              <h3>9. Maximum local snow load p<sub>max</sub></h3>
              <p>
                The “Maximum local snow load” reported by the calculator is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( p_{\text{max}} = p_{\text{roof}} + p_d + p_r \)
              </div>
              <p>
                where \(p_{\text{roof}}\) is pf (flat) or ps (sloped). This is
                useful for checking localized effects at drift locations,
                parapets, or step roofs.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and professional use</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This tool does not cover partial loading patterns, sliding
                  snow, or complex geometries.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It uses typical approximations for Ce, Ct, Cs, and drift
                  coefficients, not the full ASCE 7-22 tables.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does not replace the ASCE 7-22 standard, commentary, or
                  local amendments.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Final designs must be prepared and sealed by a licensed
                  professional engineer where required.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Is this calculator specific to ASCE 7-22?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes, it is intended to reflect the ASCE 7-22 approach to snow
                loads, including the updated ground snow load mapping
                philosophy. However, many of the core equations are similar to
                earlier editions.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use SI units (kN/m², meters)?</h3>
              <p>
                Internally the calculator works in psf and feet. To use SI
                units, convert:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>1 kN/m² ≈ 20.885 psf</li>
                <li>1 m ≈ 3.281 ft</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Enter the converted values, run the calculation, then convert
                the resulting psf back to kN/m² if needed.
              </p>

              <h3>How should I document snow load calculations?</h3>
              <p>Good practice is to show:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Source of pg (ASCE Hazard Tool screenshot or code table)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Chosen Ce, Ct, Is, Cs with references to ASCE 7-22
                  sections/tables
                </li>
                <li>Flat/sloped roof snow load equations and results</li>
                <li>Drift, unbalanced, and rain-on-snow cases considered</li>
                <li>
                  Controlling load combinations per ASCE 7-22 and your design
                  code
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>
